\subsection{State and concurrency}{

The \code{chart()} + \code{\link[=indicator]{indicator()}} pair follows the same active-target
model as base R's \code{\link[=plot]{plot()}} / \code{\link[=lines]{lines()}}. When \code{chart()} is called it
stashes a per-pipeline state object in its caller's evaluation frame;
subsequent \code{\link[=indicator]{indicator()}} calls retrieve the state by walking up the
call stack.

The practical consequences:
\itemize{
\item \code{chart()} and the subsequent \code{\link[=indicator]{indicator()}} calls must live in the
\strong{same enclosing frame} - the same REPL session, the same function
body, the same \code{renderPlot()} / \code{renderPlotly()} block, the same
\code{local({...})} expression, the same \code{testthat::test_that({...})}
block, etc. Splitting them across unrelated helpers is not
supported.
\item Two unrelated function bodies (or two parallel \code{renderPlot()}
callbacks in a Shiny app, or two \code{future::future()} blocks) each
get their own frame, so their chart states are isolated by
construction - without \code{talib} taking any dependency on Shiny,
promises, or futures.
\item Calling \code{chart()} with no arguments clears the state in the
caller's frame, mirroring a fresh \code{plot()} call on a new device.
}
}
